is not worth much to the criminal unless it prevents the repetition of his offence3 and punishment simply cannot do that. Where then the disposition to crime continues, and the opportunity is again presented, the cri- minal repeats what he has done before. If disposition cannot be altered, there remains only the other alternative; to deprive the criminal in some way for ever of the power of repeating his offcnce. If Cicero has told the truth, Piso was exactly the person who should have been treated in this way.
